<Layout title="Cognitive & Dementia Assessment Tools" description="Cognitive and dementia assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Cognitive &amp; Dementia</div>
  <h1>Cognitive &amp; Dementia Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Bedside and clinical tools for detecting and staging cognitive impairment, mild cognitive impairment, and dementia.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>MMSE (Mini-Mental State Examination)</strong> — 30-point bedside cognitive assessment: orientation, registration, attention, recall, language, and visuospatial. Score &lt;24 suggests cognitive impairment.</li>
      <li><strong>MoCA (Montreal Cognitive Assessment)</strong> — 30-point tool more sensitive than MMSE for mild cognitive impairment. Assesses visuospatial, naming, memory, attention, language, abstraction, and orientation.</li>
      <li><strong>CDR (Clinical Dementia Rating)</strong> — Five-domain staging of dementia severity: 0 (none), 0.5 (questionable), 1 (mild), 2 (moderate), 3 (severe). Based on informant and patient interviews.</li>
      <li><strong>SLUMS (Saint Louis University Mental Status Exam)</strong> — 30-point cognitive screen with high sensitivity for mild cognitive impairment; adjusts cutoffs for education level.</li>
      <li><strong>AMT (Abbreviated Mental Test)</strong> — 10-item rapid cognitive assessment for older adults. Score ≤6 indicates significant cognitive impairment; widely used in acute settings.</li>
      <li><strong>Clock Drawing Test</strong> — Executive function and visuospatial screen; patient draws a clock face with all numbers and hands set to a specified time. Multiple scoring systems available.</li>
      <li><strong>Mini-Cog</strong> — Three-item recall combined with clock drawing; highly sensitive for dementia in primary care. Takes 3 minutes to administer.</li>
      <li><strong>GPCOG (General Practitioner Assessment of Cognition)</strong> — Patient cognitive screen plus informant questionnaire; validated for primary care dementia detection.</li>
      <li><strong>SPMSQ (Short Portable Mental Status Questionnaire)</strong> — 10-item orientation and memory questionnaire; adjusts for education level. Score 0–2 errors = intact; 8–10 errors = severe impairment.</li>
      <li><strong>FAST Scale (Functional Assessment Staging Test)</strong> — Seven-stage functional progression of Alzheimer's disease from normal (Stage 1) to severe dementia with loss of ambulation and speech (Stage 7).</li>
      <li><strong>Reisberg Global Deterioration Scale (GDS)</strong> — Seven-stage cognitive and functional decline scale from no cognitive decline (Stage 1) to very severe cognitive decline (Stage 7).</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
